'''Jesse Kalisher''' (June 22, 1962 – July 20, 2017) was an American art photographer.<ref name="kalisher">{{cite web|url=http://www.kalisher.com/about.html |title=Hospitality Art |publisher=Kalisher |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021084903/http://www.kalisher.com/about.html |archivedate=2012-10-21 |df= }}</ref>

==Background==
Jesse Kalisher was barely six years old when he received his first camera. It was a birthday gift from his father, the photographer Simpson Kalisher.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Museum of Fine Arts, Houston |url=http://www.mfah.org/exhibitions/past/simpson-kalisher-alienated-photographer |title=Exhibitions &#124; Simpson Kalisher: The Alienated Photographer |publisher=MFAH |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120124041407/http://www.mfah.org/exhibitions/past/simpson-kalisher-alienated-photographer/ |archivedate=2012-01-24 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simpsonkalisher.com/info_pages/credits_01.html |title=Credits |publisher=Simpson Kalisher |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226035932/http://www.simpsonkalisher.com/info_pages/credits_01.html |archivedate=2011-02-26 |df= }}</ref> Although Jesse was raised by his mother Ilse, he worked with Simpson in the darkroom and later served as his assistant.<ref name="kalisher" />

Despite his early interest in photography, Kalisher embarked on a decade long career in marketing and advertising, working for companies including [[BBDO]], Grey Advertising, The Clorox Company, and [[J. Walter Thompson]]. Unfulfilled, he decided to leave the industry and spend a few months traveling. During a trip to Vietnam, Kalisher rediscovered his passion for photography, propelling him down the path to a new career as a fine art photographer.<ref name="digitalphotopro">{{cite web|last=Willis |first=David |url=http://www.digitalphotopro.com/profiles/jesse-kalisher-world-traveler.html |title=Jesse Kalisher: World Traveler |publisher=DigitalPhotoPro.com |date=2011-04-26 |accessdate=2012-07-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108073814/http://www.digitalphotopro.com/profiles/jesse-kalisher-world-traveler.html |archivedate=2011-11-08 |df= }}</ref>

==Career and work==
Kalisher's photography is featured in the permanent collections of museums such as the Louvre,{{Citation needed|date=November 2018|reason=A search of the collection of the Louvre art gallery in Paris, France shows there is no work by Jesse Kalisher}} The Smithsonian,{{Citation needed|date=November 2018|reason=A search of the collection of the Smithsonian Art Gallery collections returns no work by Jesse Kalisher}}  The [[George Eastman Museum]], The [[M. H. de Young Memorial Museum]] of San Francisco, The Museum of Fine Arts Houston, and many more. The first photographs of Barack Obama acquired by the Smithsonian were Kalisher's. Additionally, his photography has been exhibited in numerous galleries and several museums, including the Oakland Museum of California and Chicago's Field Museum.<ref name="kalisher" />

His work can also be found in hotels across the globe, including Hyatt, Hilton, and Sheraton. Prints of his fine art photography are sold at popular American travel destinations including the [[Grand Canyon]], the [[Golden Gate Bridge]], and the [[Empire State Building]].<ref name="digitalphotopro" />

Kalisher's photos have been published in periodicals including ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''Art Business News'', ''Black and White magazine'', ''Art & Living Magazine'' and ''Interior Design Magazine''.<ref name="kalisher" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artandliving.com/jm/us/now/artists/275 |title=Jesse Kalisher |publisher=Artandliving.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310005631/http://www.artandliving.com/jm/us/now/artists/275 |archivedate=2012-03-10 |df= }}</ref> His book ''If You Find the Buddha'', published by Chronicle Books in 2006, includes 93 images captured in Thailand and the US that depict Buddha as part of everyday life.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Kalisher, Jesse | title=If you find the Buddha | publication-date=2006 | publisher=Chronicle Books | isbn=978-0-8118-4814-5 }}</ref>

Kalisher was a faculty member at Maine Media Workshops, teaching an advanced course in black and white photography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mainemedia.edu/instructors/photo/jesse-kalisher |title=Jesse Kalisher &#124; Maine Media |publisher=Mainemedia.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100713162112/http://www.mainemedia.edu/instructors/photo/jesse-kalisher |archivedate=2010-07-13 |df= }}</ref> He has dispensed photography tips through YouTube videos<ref>{{cite web|author=Jesse Kalisher&#039;s: Story Behind the Picture |url=http://www.kalisher.com/photo_blog/?page_id=32 |title=Videos // Jesse Kalisher's: Story Behind the Picture |publisher=Kalisher.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> and shares the stories behind some of his favorite shots on his blog.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jesse Kalisher&#039;s: Story Behind the Picture |url=http://www.kalisher.com/photo_blog/ |title=Jesse Kalisher's: Story Behind the Picture |publisher=Kalisher.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> He has made TV appearances and radio broadcasts. He has been a frequent guest on National Public Radio, serving as a commentator for Marketplace and telling stories for Day to Day, Weekend America, The Savvy Traveler, and the State of Things.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themonti.org/storytellers/jesse-kalisher |title=Storytellers &#124; Jesse Kalisher &#124; |publisher=Themonti.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> He has also led photography expeditions for Regent Seven Sea Cruises and Paul Gauguin Cruises.<ref name="digitalphotopro" />

Kalisher was the founder and President of Kalisher, an eponymous art gallery. Based in [[Carrboro, North Carolina]], Kalisher was a provider of art for the hospitality industry.

Kalisher was a 1984 graduate of [[Northwestern University]].

