rmany}} |born 1929 |Achievements in social philosophy, in particular establishment of the communicative action theory and discourse ethics, and its application in practical activities for a public-minded ideal society<ref>{{cite web | title = Jürgen Habermas | publisher = Inamori Foundation | url = http://www.kyotoprize.org/en/laureates/jurgen_habermas/ | accessdate = 2016-10-15}}</ref> |- |2008 |[[Image:Charles Taylor.jpg|75px]] |[[Charles Taylor (philosopher)|Charles Margrave Taylor]] |{{flagcountry|Canada}} |born 1931 |Construction of a Social Philosophy to Pursue the Coexistence of Diverse Cultures<ref>{{cite web | title = Charles Margrave Taylor | publisher = Inamori Foundation | url = http://www.kyotoprize.org/en/laureates/charles_margrave_taylor/ | accessdate = 2016-10-15}}</ref> |- |2012 |[[Image:Gayatri Spivak on Subversive Festival.jpg|75px]] |[[Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak]] |{{flagcountry|India}} |born 1942 |A Critical Theorist and Educator Speaking for the Humanities Against Intellectual Colonialism in Relation to the Globalized World<ref>{{cite web | title = Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak | publisher = Inamori Foundation | url = http://www.kyotoprize.org/en/laureates/gayatri_chakravorty_spivak/ | accessdate = 2016-10-15}}</ref> |- |2016 |[[Image:Martha Nussbaum.jpg|75px]] |[[Martha Craven Nussbaum]] |{{flagcountry|United States}} |born 1947 |A Philosopher Who Has Developed a New Theory of Justice Advocating the Capabilities Approach<ref>{{cite web | title = Martha Craven Nussbaum | publisher = Inamori Foundation | url = http://www.kyotoprize.org/en/laureates/martha_craven_nussbaum/ | accessdate = 2016-10-15}}</ref> |}
