{{Infobox Neighborhood Portland OR | name = Pearl District | association_name = Pearl District Neighborhood Association | association_website = http://www.pearldistrict.org/ | coalition_name = Neighbors West/Northwest | coalition_website = http://www.nwnw.org/ | area_km2 = 1.21 | map_url = http://www.portlandonline.com/oni/index.cfm?c=35281&a=58616 | coordinates = {{coord|45.53012|-122.68136|format=dms|region:US-OR_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | portlandmaps_x = 7643159.605 | portlandmaps_y = 686914.544 | censusyear = 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portlandmaps.com/detail.cfm?action=Census&x=7643159.605&y=686914.544|title=PortlandMaps|author=|date=|website=www.portlandmaps.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221005459/http://www.portlandmaps.com/detail.cfm?action=Census&x=7643159.605&y=686914.544|archivedate=21 February 2008|df=}}</ref> | pop_total = 5997 | households_total = 5315 | occupancy = 79 | households_owned = 1493 | households_owned_pct = 28 | households_rented = 2699 | households_rented_pct = 51 | household_size = 1.13 }}
The '''Pearl District''' is an area of [[Portland, Oregon]], formerly occupied by [[warehouse]]s, light [[industry]] and [[railroad]] [[classification yard]]s and now noted for its [[art gallery|art galleries]], upscale businesses and residences. The area has been undergoing significant [[urban renewal]] since the mid-1980s when it was reclassified as [[mixed use]] from industrial,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marshall-wells.com/historypearl3.html|title=Marshall-Wells Lofts <> History|author=|date=|website=www.marshall-wells.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225132726/http://www.marshall-wells.com/historypearl3.html|archivedate=25 February 2017|df=}}</ref> including the arrival of artists, the removal of a [[viaduct]] and construction of the [[Portland Streetcar]]. It now mostly consists of high-rise [[condominium]]s and [[loft apartment|warehouse-to-loft conversions]].
The increase of high-rise condominiums and warehouse-to-loft conversions was made evident with the construction of the [[Cosmopolitan on the Park]] building, which opened in Summer 2016. The Cosmopolitan on the Park residential building is now the tallest building in the Pearl District and the 8th tallest building in Portland, contributing to the changing Portland skyline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nextportland.com/2014/12/09/cosmopolitan-on-the-park/|title=North Pearl High-Rises, Part I: The Cosmopolitan on the Park (images)|last=Nextportland|date=2014-12-09|website=Next Portland|access-date=2017-01-31|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202091637/http://www.nextportland.com/2014/12/09/cosmopolitan-on-the-park/|archivedate=2017-02-02|df=}}</ref>
The area is located just northwest of [[Downtown, Portland, Oregon|downtown]] between West Burnside Street on the south, the [[Willamette River]] on the north, NW Broadway on the east and the [[Interstate 405 (Oregon)|Interstate 405]] [[freeway]] on the west.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portlandonline.com/oni/index.cfm?c=35281&a=58616 |title=Pearl Neighborhood Association boundary map |format=[[PDF]] |date=June 1, 2001 |author=City of [[Portland, Oregon]] Office of Neighborhood Involvement/Bureau of Planning |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202094311/http://www.portlandonline.com/oni/index.cfm?c=35281&a=58616 |archivedate=December 2, 2008 |df= }}</ref>
The area is home to several Portland icons, including [[Powell's City of Books]]. The former [[Henry Weinhard|Weinhard]] Brewery, which operated continuously from 1864 to September 1999, was shut down by Stroh's upon the purchase of the Weinhard's brand by [[Miller Brewing]] and sold for redevelopment as the Brewery Blocks.<ref>[http://www.architectureweek.com/2005/0511/environment_1-1.html "Mixed Use Brewery Blocks"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610011611/http://www.architectureweek.com/2005/0511/environment_1-1.html |date=2008-06-10 }}. Accessed online 16 July 2008.</ref> There are [[List of artists and art institutions in Portland, Oregon|art galleries and institutions]] such as the Elizabeth Leach Gallery and [[Blue Sky Gallery]] (many who stage monthly receptions), boutiques, and restaurants abound, and also a number of small clubs and bars, a combination that has led to Pearl District being named one of the 15 coolest neighborhoods in the world in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 15 Coolest Neighborhoods in the World in 2016|url=http://www.howitravel.co/the-15-coolest-neighborhoods-in-the-world-in-2016/|accessdate=13 November 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203011043/http://www.howitravel.co/the-15-coolest-neighborhoods-in-the-world-in-2016/|archivedate=3 December 2016|df=}}</ref> The [[United States Postal Service|United States Post Office]] main processing facility for all of Oregon and southwestern Washington was built in the Pearl District in 1964, next to [[Union Station (Portland)|Union Station]]. This location was chosen in order for the post office to be able to better serve towns outside the Portland metro area.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}
The district includes most of the historic{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} [[North Park Blocks]] (1869), as well as three public plazas: *[[Jamison Square]] (2002) is built around a fountain which simulates a tidal pool that is periodically filled by [[artificial waterfall]]s and then drained into grating. *[[Tanner Springs Park]] (2005) is a re-created natural area featuring wetlands, a walking trail, and creek. *[[The Fields Park]] (2013) is a Neighborhood and Dog Park in the Northern part of the Pearl.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Fields Park|url=http://www.portlandonline.com/parks/index.cfm?c=44338|publisher=City of Portland|accessdate=12 July 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629014845/http://www.portlandonline.com/PARKS/index.cfm?c=44338|archivedate=29 June 2011|df=}}</ref> The Park provides space for visual or performing arts, for community-building activities and has a large paved walking loop.
==History== The area was formerly used for [[warehouse|warehousing]], light [[Industry|industrial]] purposes and a [[railroad]] yard and was known as the "Northwest Industrial Triangle".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=29660 |title=More polish for the Pearl |author=Don Hamilton |work=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=April 29, 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221234201/http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=29660|archivedate=February 21, 2008|accessdate=January 31, 2015}}</ref>
In the 1990s, the Lovejoy Viaduct, an elevated portion of NW Lovejoy Street from the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]] past NW 10th Avenue was demolished, opening dozens of surrounding blocks (including some [[brownfield]] sites) for development, which peaked in the 2000s. The viaduct was notable for the [[Lovejoy Columns]], painted by a railroad watchman who worked below; two of them have been saved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chatterbox.typepad.com/portlandarchitecture/2005/10/more_on_the_lov.html|title=More on the Lovejoy Columns|author=|date=|website=Portland Architecture|accessdate=24 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150604111614/http://chatterbox.typepad.com/portlandarchitecture/2005/10/more_on_the_lov.html|archivedate=4 June 2015|df=}}</ref> The increasing density has attracted a mix of restaurants, [[brewpub]]s, shops, and art galleries.
The origins of how the Pearl District got its name is still up for debate. According to the Pearl District Business Association, Thomas Augustine, a local gallery owner, coined the name Pearl District around the turn of the millennium to suggest that some of its urban decay industrial buildings were like crusty oysters, and that the galleries and artists' lofts within were like pearls. However, in 2002, Thomas Augustine amended his story, suggesting that the idea for the Pearl District came from his friend Pearl Marie Amhara who would throw parties for creatives in warehouses in what is now considered the Pearl District. Attendees started calling the area “Pearl’s place” and “Pearl’s District”. Local business people were looking to label the growing area and the name finally caught on when a writer for [[Alaska Airlines]] borrowed and popularized Augustine's phrase. The "warehouse district" or the "brewery district" were two other suggestions that are still used today.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2002/04/pearl_districts_namesake_was_a.html | work=[[The Oregonian]] | author=Margie Boule | date=April 14, 2002 | title=Pearl District's namesake was a jewel of a woman | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410221052/http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2002/04/pearl_districts_namesake_was_a.html | archivedate=April 10, 2015 | df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pearldistrict.org/pearl-district-name/|title=How Did the Pearl District Get Its Name?|date=2014-01-06|newspaper=Pearl District Neighborhood Association|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-31|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912063619/http://www.pearldistrict.org/pearl-district-name/|archivedate=2015-09-12|df=}}</ref>
The movie ''[[Drugstore Cowboy]]'' (1989), by [[Gus Van Sant]], has several scenes shot in the neighborhood.
